Another useful OpenGL macro, at least for me, is this one:<p><pre><code>    #define GLSL(str) (char*)&quot;#version 330
&quot; #str
</code></pre>
It basically enables you to embed quick snippets of GLSL inside your C code, instead of using concatenated strings. Example:<p><pre><code>    char* fragShader = GLSL(
      in vec3 uv;
      out vec4 color;
      uniform sampler2DArray tex;
      void main()
      {
        // Comments work too
        color = texture(tex, uv);
      }
    );
</code></pre>
In Sublime Text you even get code completion and color highlighting, since GLSL and C look so alike.<p>I believe it might work for OpenCL Kernels too.<p>The only downside is that it doesn&#x27;t add line breaks by itself (hence the &quot;#version 330
&quot;, which requires a line break), so GLSL Compilation errors aren&#x27;t as useful.<p>(Source: <a href="https://open.gl/geometry" rel="nofollow">https://open.gl/geometry</a> )
